54//
55// Interrupt Enable Register Allocation For 2833x Devices:
56//
57// Interrupts can be enabled/disabled using the CPU interrupt enable register
58// (IER) and the PIE interrupt enable registers (PIEIER1 to PIEIER12).
59//
60//
61// Set "Global" Interrupt Priority Level (IER register):
62//
63// The user must set the appropriate priority level for each of the CPU
64// interrupts. This is termed as the "global" priority. The priority level
65// must be a number between 1 (highest) to 16 (lowest). A value of 0 must
66// be entered for reserved interrupts or interrupts that are not used. This
67// will also reduce code size by not including ISR's that are not used.
68//
69// Note: The priority levels below are used to calculate the IER register
70// interrupt masks MINT1 to MINT16.
71//
72//
73// Note: The priority levels shown here may not make sense in a
74// real application. This is for demonstration purposes only!!!
75//
76// The user should change these to values that make sense for
77// their application.
78//
79// 0 = not used
80// 1 = highest priority
81// ...
82// 16 = lowest priority
83//
84#define INT1PL 2 // Group1 Interrupts (PIEIER1)
85#define INT2PL 1 // Group2 Interrupts (PIEIER2)
86#define INT3PL 4 // Group3 Interrupts (PIEIER3)
87#define INT4PL 2 // Group4 Interrupts (PIEIER4)
88#define INT5PL 2 // Group5 Interrupts (PIEIER5)
89#define INT6PL 3 // Group6 Interrupts (PIEIER6)
90#define INT7PL 0 // reserved
91#define INT8PL 0 // reserved
92#define INT9PL 3 // Group9 Interrupts (PIEIER9)
93#define INT10PL 0 // reserved
94#define INT11PL 0 // reserved
95#define INT12PL 0 // reserved
96#define INT13PL 4 // XINT13
97#define INT14PL 4 // INT14 (TINT2)
98#define INT15PL 4 // DATALOG
99#define INT16PL 4 // RTOSINT
100
101//
102// Set "Group" Interrupt Priority Level (PIEIER1 to PIEIER12 registers):
103//
104// The user must set the appropriate priority level for each of the PIE
105// interrupts. This is termed as the "group" priority. The priority level
106// must be a number between 1 (highest) to 8 (lowest). A value of 0 must
107// be entered for reserved interrupts or interrupts that are not used. This
108// will also reduce code size by not including ISR's that are not used:
109//
110// Note: The priority levels below are used to calculate the following
111// PIEIER register interrupt masks:
112// MG11 to MG18
113// MG21 to MG28
114// MG31 to MG38
115// MG41 to MG48
116// MG51 to MG58
117// MG61 to MG68
118// MG71 to MG78
119// MG81 to MG88
120// MG91 to MG98
121// MG101 to MG108
122// MG111 to MG118
123// MG121 to MG128
124//
125// Note: The priority levels shown here may not make sense in a
126// real application. This is for demonstration purposes only!!!
127//
128// The user should change these to values that make sense for
129// their application.
130//
131// 0 = not used
132// 1 = highest priority
133// ...
134// 8 = lowest priority
135//

137#define G12PL 6 // SEQ2INT (ADC)
138#define G13PL 0 // reserved
139#define G14PL 1 // XINT1 (External)

141#define G16PL 2 // ADCINT (ADC)
142#define G17PL 1 // TINT0 (CPU Timer 0)
143#define G18PL 5 // WAKEINT (WD/LPM)
